<DOC><DOCNO> AP890401-0100 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-89 1734EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-01 0432</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0442</SECOND><HEAD>Snow in Colorado, Northeast; Rain in Midwest</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   As much as a foot of fresh snow fell on the Colorado Rockies onSaturday, and about six inches fell in parts of New York state andVermont before an Eastern storm began to fizzle.   A cold front moved across the upper Mississippi Valley and thecentral Plains, producing rain from Iowa into western Wisconsin.Wet snow fell in central and northern Minnesota.   Light snow tapered off across portions of the centralAppalachians and northern New England after dumping a half foot ofsnow across the Adirondacks and the St. Lawrence River valley ofNew York state and Vermont.   Snowfall totals early Saturday included 6 inches at Massena andRochester, NY., 5 inches at Buffalo, N.Y., and 3 inches at St.Albans, Vt.   Heavy snow fell over the northern and central mountains ofColorado, where overnight accumulations included 12{ inches at Vailand 11{ inches at the Beaver Creek ski area.   Snow and strong winds made driving difficult over mountainpasses. An advisory for snow and blowing snow was posted for thenorthern and central mountains of Colorado.   In the far West, a cold front produced rain over the PacificNorthwest. Snow advisories were posted for the Cascades ofWashington state and northern Oregon.   Another cold front moving across Southern California broughtgusty winds to the Mojave Desert.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 29degrees at Caribou and Limestone, Maine, and Saranac Lake, N.Y., to89 degrees at Thermal, Calif.   The low in the nation Saturday morning was 8 degrees atMarquette, Mich.   The National Weather Service forecast for Sunday called forscattered rainshowers from western Kansas across much of the middleMississippi Valley, southern portions of the upper Great Lakes andthe Ohio Valley to the central Appalachians; rain falling acrossmuch of the northern and central Pacific Coast and the northern andcentral Intermountain region; and strong, gusty winds across thenorthern and central Rockies.   High temperatures were expected to be in the 30s over northeastMinnesota, northwest Wisconsin, western upper Michigan and northernMaine; in the 40s and 50s from the Pacific Northwest across thenorthern and central Rockies, North Dakota, much of the upperMississippi Valley and the Great Lakes to the northern AtlanticCoast; the 80s over all of Texas except the panhandle to southernportions of the southern plateau; and in the 90s in parts of thedesert Southwest. The remainder of the nation generally wasexpected to have high temperatures in the 60s and 70s.</TEXT></DOC>